## BLOCKER DETECTION (Subtask 1 MUST include)

The Quick Recon subtask MUST detect blockers:
- WAF presence (DataDome, Cloudflare, Akamai) via test requests
- Auth endpoint accessibility — note CAPTCHA, phone verification, PayPal, KYC requirements
- Rate limiting detection
- Accessible vs blocked endpoint mapping
- Write blockers to HANDOFF.md as `[BLOCKER: type]`
- End with "BLOCKERS DETECTED" section listing what's blocked, affected categories, and recommended adjustments

## SUBTASK DEDUPLICATION

- NEVER create two subtasks with same/overlapping objective
- Combine related tool runs into one subtask
- Maximum 1 subtask per major phase
- BAD: "Scan with nuclei" + "Run nuclei focused" + "Nuclei comprehensive" → MERGE into one
- Before finalizing, merge any subtasks a human would call "basically the same thing"

## ONE VULNERABILITY CLASS PER SUBTASK — THE IRON RULE

**⚠️ #1 cause of wasted budget. Multi-class subtasks ALWAYS timeout.**

Data from real executions:
- Single-class: **95%+ completion**
- 2-class: **~40% completion** (timeout before second class)
- 3+ class: **~5% completion**

### Validation Test
For each subtask: "Does it mention >1 vulnerability class?"
- YES → SPLIT into separate subtasks
- Title contains "and"/"&" joining DIFFERENT vuln types → SPLIT
- Sub-techniques within ONE class are OK: "blind SSRF and server-side SSRF" (both SSRF)
- Different classes are NEVER OK: "SSRF and IDOR" → SPLIT

**When in doubt, split.** Two 15-minute subtasks > one 35-minute timeout.

## TARGET ISOLATION RULE

- Each subtask targets a SINGLE domain/host
- Multiple targets → SEPARATE subtask groups per target
- Cross-target subtasks ONLY after all per-target testing complete
- Final report may cover all targets

